WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.680
to talk about CAR-T-cells and allotransplant. It's kind of funny, you know, the leukemia docs

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:08.900
listen to the lymphoma and myeloma docs talk about whether autotransplantation is dead. And

00:00:08.900 --> 00:00:14.140
in the ALL world, we're trying to figure out how to get rid of the use of allogeneic transplantation

00:00:14.140 --> 00:00:18.480
and do CAR-T-cells get us there. And I'm going to make a case that right now, probably not yet.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:23.060
So we all know that CAR-T-cells are very important for management of relapsed refractory ALL,

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:27.660
but the pivotal trials that led to the approval of brexit cell and OB cell, which are our main

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:32.420
broadly available CAR-T-cells for adults, left a lot of unanswered questions, primarily because

00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:37.600
both studies included a substantial portion of patients who had previously had an allotransplant

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:42.140
and it didn't specify whether patients should receive a consolidative ALL after the CAR-T-cell.

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:46.740
So we have a lot of questions from these studies. And there's a few different ways that one can

00:00:46.740 --> 00:00:51.380
receive a CAR-T-cell for relapsed refractory ALL. You can either receive it as destination therapy

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:55.780
without a transplant, you can receive a consolidative allotransplant after the CAR-T-cell,

00:00:55.780 --> 00:00:57.480
or you may receive the CAR-T-cell

00:00:57.480 --> 00:00:57.640
for relapsed refractory ALL.

00:00:57.660 --> 00:01:02.040
a post-transplant relapse. And then in rare cases, one could consider a second transplant

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.780
after that scenario. So if we look at the data from the ZUMA3 study, which led to the approval

00:01:06.780 --> 00:01:12.860
of brexit cell, there did not appear to be a different outcome on the left side for patients

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:17.580
who did or did not have a prior allotransplant, nor did there appear to be a difference on the

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:22.200
right side for patients who had a consolidative allotransplant or not. But this is a relatively

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:27.480
small study. There are only 51 patients in the phase two. And when we combine those who got

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:32.140
the pivotal dose in phase one, it's still only 78 patients. So this really wasn't designed to

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:36.860
answer this question. On the FELIX study, which led to the approval of OB cell, there is no

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:42.360
difference in outcomes if we censor or not for the use of subsequent alginate transplantation.

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:47.600
However, in a multivariate analysis presented by Jay Park at ASCO last year, we do see that

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:51.920
there is a significant impact, apparently, to having a prior alginate transplant before

00:01:51.920 --> 00:01:57.360
receiving OB cell. And so if we look at the outcomes for alginate transplantation for

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:03.840
relapsed refractory ALL, you see here the bar for C2 and beyond, it really is a long-term survival,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:09.560
about 50%. And to me, this is the bar that needs to be overcome by CAR-T cells for us to say that

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:14.420
we're going to relegate allotransplantation in this particular setting. And those CAR-T cells

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:19.080
don't appear to be getting us there. So because there are so many unanswered questions from these

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:23.860
clinical trials, it's really incumbent upon us as a community to gather our data in the real world

00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:27.240
to address some of these questions. We're now doing this with ALL.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:31.920
through the ROCA consortium, which is aggregating data from more than 40 U.S. institutions.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:37.900
And the first publication came out a little more than a year ago from the first 189 patients

00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:42.560
infused in the commercial setting with Brexacel. And we saw that the outcomes really recapitulated

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:48.760
the ZUMA3 trial, showing that this is a reliable data set to start answering some of these

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:53.680
unanswered questions. And even from this analysis of the first 189 patients,

00:02:53.680 --> 00:02:57.120
we can see that there appears in the real world to be a benefit

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:03.360
both to having had a prior transplant or to having a subsequent algenic transplant after Brexacel

00:03:03.360 --> 00:03:09.080
in the real world. And so we wanted to answer this question as cleanly as possible. So we

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:13.020
continue to gather more patients in this database. There's now about 350 patients

00:03:13.020 --> 00:03:19.100
who have received Brexacel in the real world. We found 164 patients, all pH-B cell ALL,

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:25.520
who achieved an MRD-negative remission, either flow or NGS, after the CAR-T cell as measured at

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:27.000
one month. And we

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.420
broke these patients down into those who had never had a transplant, those who had a post-CAR-T cell

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:38.640
consolidated allotransplant, or those who had had a pre-CAR-T cell transplant, namely they got the

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:43.940
CAR-T cell for post-transplant relapse. We actually excluded the very small number of patients who had

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:48.700
two transplants. This doesn't happen very frequently in the real world. We didn't think that only nine

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:54.760
patients would really lead to a reliable assessment. So when we break these patients down, we see that

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:56.880
there were substantially larger patients who had a pre-CAR-T cell as measured at one month. And we

00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:01.440
also have a larger number of young patients who had a post-CAR-T cell consolidated allotransplant. And

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:06.540
there were more patients who had a post-CAR-T cell consolidated allotransplant who had non-CNS

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:11.820
extramedullary disease. On the other side, we see that there were more patients of advanced age who

00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:17.360
never had a transplant in this setting. We really wanted to address the question, for those who had

00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:22.760
a transplant before and then relapsed and then got to CAR-T cells, whose T cells are making those

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:26.520
CAR-T cells? So we obtained chimerism data for,

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:32.160
as many of these patients as we could. This is not collected necessarily systematically at all centers.

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:36.600
We were able to get data on 28 patients. We found that the majority of these patients were indeed

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:41.640
full donor chimeras at the time that they had their apheresis, meaning that their CAR-T cells

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:45.240
were indeed allogeneic CAR-T cells. So does this have an impact?

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:50.160
So if we look at this, these outcomes with about a year of follow-up, we can see

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:56.640
that at one year, the best outcomes are for those who had a post-CAR-T cell consolidated allotransplant.

00:04:56.640 --> 00:05:03.700
78% one-year survival. Next is those patients who had a prior transplant before the CAR-T cells

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:09.760
at 58%. And the worst outcome is in those who never had a transplant. Now, of course, we can't

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:14.960
directly compare these curves to one another because there's an immortal time bias for those

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:19.940
who went on to receive a subsequent transplant. So if we landmark at day 73, which is the median

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:25.740
time to a post-CAR-T cell transplant, we can see very interestingly that those who achieve and

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:32.100
remission until two and a half months after CAR-T cells enjoy the same benefit if they had a prior

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:37.480
transplant as if they had a post-CAR-T cell transplant. So there does seem to be an impact

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:42.520
to receiving allogeneic CAR-T cells in the setting. And, you know, unfortunately, those patients who

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:46.640
never had a transplant have the worst outcomes. With this one year of follow-up, we don't yet

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:51.660
see overall survival differences, but we will continue to follow. So we did want to try and

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:56.400
address the question with the data that we have, who may be the best candidate for never

00:05:56.400 --> 00:06:02.080
receiving an allotransplant when using CAR-T cells for relapsed refractory ALL. And interestingly,

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:07.400
the outcomes are best for patients of more advanced age. So patients over age 60 here are

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:12.180
doing better, patients who have non-PH-like disease, and those who are MRD negative prior

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:16.920
to the apheresis, meaning that they got salvage therapy, had a great response to it, went on to

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:23.180
receive an apheresis and a CAR-T cell, and then did very well. So I'll just conclude by saying

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:26.280
one of our findings is the vast majority of patients who get CAR-T cells, they're not

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:30.880
getting allogeneic CAR-T cells in the post-transplant relapse setting, are getting allogeneic CAR

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:35.680
T cells. And those patients have a better outcome than patients who never have a transplant. This

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:40.640
raises some very interesting questions. Is it because they're invigorating some kind of

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:46.160
graft-versus-leukemia effect? Are the T cells simply of better fitness because they have not

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:51.840
gone through multiple cycles of chemotherapy? Or is there something else going on? Patients who

00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:56.160
did not have a prior transplant and got Brexacel in the real-world setting did better,

00:06:56.160 --> 00:07:00.920
if they received a consolidative allo. And on the basis of these data, the Rocket Consortium

00:07:00.920 --> 00:07:04.760
does recommend that if a patient has never had an allotransplant and they're receiving

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:11.800
Brexacel for relapse, that they should probably go on to a consolidated allotransplant.

00:07:12.280 --> 00:07:16.080
But if you wanted to pick the people who you might avoid transplant, it's going to be the

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:21.040
older patients, non-PH-like disease, who have a great response to salvage before the apheresis,

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:25.360
and there you might be able to avoid it. Hopefully with additional data, we'll have even

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:30.400
more precise measures for predicting who can do well without transplant.

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:35.040
And with that, I'm going to thank everyone from the Rocket Consortium who collected these data.

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:38.340
This is a lot of work at each of the centers, and it wouldn't be possible for us to answer

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:41.040
these questions without everyone's help. So thank you very much.
